# Email 1 — Inconsistent Dater

**Subject:** Your quiz results: You don't have a dating problem. You have a consistency problem.

---

You scored as the **Inconsistent Dater** — and here's the thing: there's actually a lot working in your favor. You're emotionally ready. Your signal reading isn't terrible. You're not carrying a ton of unprocessed baggage. But if I watched a highlight reel of your dating life over the past few months, it would look like two completely different people. And that inconsistency is the thing that's killing your results.

## The Pattern You're In

You don't have one strategy. You have two — and they alternate based on how you're feeling on any given day.

When you're confident, when a conversation is flowing, when a woman is clearly interested — you're great. You're engaging, you're funny, you initiate plans, you follow through. You look like a guy who has his shit together. In those moments, you might even wonder what the problem is. "I'm fine at this. Why don't things work out?"

Then doubt creeps in. She takes a while to respond. A date is good but not electric. You're not sure if she's into it. And you flip. You pull back. You stop texting first. You get vague about plans. You become the guy who "seems like he's not that interested" — because you're protecting yourself from potential rejection by preemptively withdrawing.

Here's what women experience: A guy who's really into them one week and distant the next. A guy who plans an amazing first date and then goes radio silent for three days. A guy who matches their energy when things are good and disappears when things get uncertain. And from her perspective, that looks like one thing: inconsistency. Which translates to: unreliable. Which translates to: not worth investing in.

You're not unreliable. You're reactive. Your strategy changes based on your emotional state instead of a consistent framework. When you feel good, you act one way. When you feel anxious, you act another way. The result is a dating experience that feels like winging it every single time — because it IS winging it every single time. You don't have a playbook. You have moods.

And the over-correction makes it worse. After a phase of being too passive, you recognize it and swing too far the other way — texting too much, planning too aggressively, coming on too strong. Then that feels wrong, so you pull back again. You're oscillating between extremes, never finding the middle. And every swing teaches the woman across from you that she can't predict what version of you is going to show up next.

## Your 3 Blind Spots

**1. Mood-based strategy.**
Your approach to dating is dictated by your emotional weather, not by a consistent set of principles. Good mood = chase. Bad mood = retreat. This means your behavior is unpredictable — to her AND to you. You can't build something stable on a foundation that shifts every 48 hours. You need a framework that operates independently of how you feel on Tuesday.

**2. Over-correction cycles.**
You recognize when you've been too passive, so you overcorrect to active. You recognize when you've been too aggressive, so you overcorrect to passive. Each correction overshoots the mark, creating a pendulum that never settles in the middle. The fix isn't to correct harder — it's to narrow the range. Small adjustments, not full reversals.

**3. No repeatable framework.**
Every dating situation feels like a brand new problem because you're solving it from scratch each time. Should I text first? Should I wait? Should I suggest plans or let her? You're re-deriving the answer every time based on feelings instead of principles. This is exhausting, and it produces inconsistent results. What you need isn't more emotional intelligence — it's a system.

## Your Action Plan (This Week)

**1. Write your "Default Mode" rules.** Three to five simple principles that you follow regardless of mood. Example: "I always text within 24 hours after a date." "I suggest the next meetup, not her." "I don't double-text — one message, then wait." These aren't rigid rules. They're your baseline. You can deviate when you have a good reason — but "I'm feeling anxious" isn't a good reason.

**2. The morning check-in.** Every morning this week, take 10 seconds to ask yourself: "Am I in chase mode or retreat mode right now?" Just notice. You don't have to change anything yet. Awareness of which mode you're in is the first step to not being controlled by it. If you're in chase mode, dial back 20%. If you're in retreat mode, push forward 20%. Small adjustments.

**3. Pick ONE active dating situation and apply your Default Mode for the full week.** Don't deviate. Even when it feels wrong. Even when your gut says "text her again" or "pull back." Follow the framework. At the end of the week, evaluate: Did consistent behavior produce better results than reactive behavior? (Spoiler: It will.)

**4. After every interaction this week, rate your behavior 1-5 on consistency.** Not "did it go well?" — that's outcome-dependent and you can't control it. Just: "Did I show up the same way I would have on my best day?" Tracking consistency instead of outcomes rewires how you evaluate your performance.

